"This increasing trend falls under the umbrella of cross-disciplinary research in which a shift in traditional academic practices involving collaboration trumps indi-vidual achievement, creating a culture of collaboration, a collaboration cosmoplitan-ism, or a team science revolution (Bozeman & Youtie, 2017).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Cross-Disciplinary Collaboration
When dealing with cross-disciplinary research, multiple agents from differing disci-plines are involved in exchanging multiple perspectives, philosophies, and theories aimed toward the phenomenon and research problem.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Some of the benefits of conduct-ing cross-disciplinary collaboration research follow:
••Complex modern problems such as climate change and resource security are not amenable to single-discipline investigation.",1523422319886300.pdf
••Discoveries are said to be more likely on the boundaries between fields.,1523422319886300.pdf
"••These encounters with others benefit single disciplines, extending their hori-zons (Rylance, 2015, p. 313).",1523422319886300.pdf
"However, even with the numerous benefits, cross-disciplinary research comes 
with many challenges as well.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Addressing these challenges and issues when conduct-ing cross-disciplinary research is the focus of the field of the Science of Team Science (SciTS; Falk-Krzesinski et al., 2010).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Building upon knowledge gained from the field 
of Team Science (TSci), SciTS has concentrated efforts primarily on conducting cross-disciplinary research.",1523422319886300.pdf
"The field of SciTS is “concerned with understanding and managing circumstances that facilitate or hinder the effectiveness of collaborative cross-disciplinary science, and the evaluation of collaborative science outcomes” (Falk-Krzesinski et al., 2010, p. 263).",1523422319886300.pdf
"TSci views cross-disciplinary research as a 
“process of teamwork to be mastered” (Fiore, 2008, p. 256).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Depending on the level of complexity in a research problem, there are generally 
four different types of cross-disciplinary collaboration research models (i.e., uni-disciplinary, multidisciplinary, interdisciplinary, transdisciplinary).",1523422319886300.pdf
Unidisciplinary includes research that is conducted within a single discipline.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Multidisciplinary includes research that involves contributions from multiple disciplines (DeHart, 2017), defined as the “coordinated efforts of some set of disciplines designed to achieve some common goal or goals” (Fiore, 2008, p. 254).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Interdisciplinary involves integrative contributions from multiple disciplines; this integration is nec-essary as no single discipline can address the issue alone (DeHart, 2017).",1523422319886300.pdf
"The out-come of interdisciplinary research often involves new ways of understanding, new lexicon to describe an emerging phenomena, and new techniques in developing new theories (Fiore, 2008).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Transdisciplinary research, in contrast, involves multiple disciplines bringing novel 
contributions to a study (DeHart, 2017).",1523422319886300.pdf
One example of transdisciplinary is when a new method needs to be developed to address a problem because existing methods are,1523422319886300.pdf
"78 Advances in Developing Human Resources 22(1)
not adequate for the stated problem.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Transdisciplinary also involves, at times, stake-
holders and community members as part of the research effort (DeHart, 2017).",1523422319886300.pdf
"The following sections identify what teamwork and taskwork entail along with an 
introduction of the critical components that a researcher should concentrate on when working in a team setting.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Then, team contracts are discussed along with collaborative research agreements that need to be decided in advance of beginning research.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Last, an introduction of contextual factors for conducting cross-disciplinary collaborations is presented.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Teamwork and Taskwork
For teams, processes are divided into two types, teamwork and taskwork.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Teamwork identifies the interactions required among team members to achieve their tasks, whereas taskwork involves the activities that must be completed to complete the team’s task or objective.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Teamwork relates to team member interactions, the sharing of information required at any point in time for team members to complete their tasks, the knowledge of who has what skills so that they can easily be identified when required, and basic com-munication among team members throughout the process.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Taskwork refers to the actual activities (technical, physical, procedural) involved in completing a task or subtask.",1523422319886300.pdf
"The field of team science has identified nine core processes that make up team-
work.",1523422319886300.pdf
"These nine core processes have been categorized as being either an emerging state (coaching, cognition, conflict, cooperation, and coordination) or an influencing condition (context, composition, and culture; Dihn & Salas, 2017; Turner et al., 2018).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Emerging states relate to internal team dynamics that can be managed, whereas influ-encing conditions are external dynamics in which the team has little control.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Identifying the conditions that can be managed compared with those that cannot be 
managed would support the efforts of scholars and scholar-practitioners in any col-laborative endeavor.",1523422319886300.pdf
"For example, it is important for new scholars to identify what the context is for their new academic home.",1523422319886300.pdf
Comparing a department’s research interest with one’s own research agenda would aid new scholars to identify better with their colleagues and the department.,1523422319886300.pdf
"In the short-term, the new scholar would not be able to make changes if their research agenda was not in line with their new academic home.",1523422319886300.pdf
This new scholar would most likely have to alter an existing research agenda to meet the department’s needs.,1523422319886300.pdf
This is an example of having little to no control over the influ-encing conditions.,1523422319886300.pdf
Scholar-practitioners would benefit from identifying with the emerging states that they can contribute to in a positive manner.,1523422319886300.pdf
By better contributing to some of these emerging states will place a scholar-practitioner in the role of a team player and potentially as an appointed team leader.,1523422319886300.pdf
This is just one example of how scholar-practitioners can influence teamwork by identifying with the emerging states.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Techniques for Collaborating
Teamwork activities requires each team member to work both independently and interdependently.",1523422319886300.pdf
Team members are required to work interdependently to “the extent,1523422319886300.pdf
"Turner and Baker 79
to which a job is contingent on others’ work” (Cordery & Tian, 2017, p. 111).",1523422319886300.pdf
Resulting in team members being dependent on other team members completing their tasks.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Task interdependence requires decisions at the team level involving “the specialization and differentiation of activities and tasks within teams, where the separation of activity elements generates explicit coordination requirements, or through the application of formalized routines that specify particular task and work flows” (p. 111).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Essentially, successful teaming requires monitoring and managing these emergent states (coaching, cognition, conflict, cooperation, and coordination) by all team members.",1523422319886300.pdf
Planning a team’s activities/goals/tasks takes work.,1523422319886300.pdf
"One common mistake that is 
often realized when beginning cross-disciplinary collaborations is in underestimating the level of commitment and personal relationships required in such an effort (Ledford, 2015).",1523422319886300.pdf
Each of the emerging states of teamwork must be managed throughout the pro-cess.,1523422319886300.pdf
One tool for managing these emerging states can be found in Figure 2.,1523422319886300.pdf
Figure 2 provides a brief example of a team agreement contract that each team member contrib-utes to.,1523422319886300.pdf
"A team or collaborative agreement should cover a team’s goals and schedule, information pertaining to who will perform which tasks and when, credit for task accomplishment acknowledged by peers (other team members), contingencies around communicating, and any conflicts of interests (Bennett & Gadlin, 2012).",1523422319886300.pdf
"The team agreement contract in Figure 2 provides information on who is on the 
team along with the team’s name.",1523422319886300.pdf
"When completing this form, team members will have an opportunity to get to know the other team members as well as their knowl-edge, skills, experiences, and area of expertise (discipline).",1523422319886300.pdf
The action of includ-ing a name for the team helps to begin forming a sense of team identify among the team members.,1523422319886300.pdf
"These initial activities will help in developing transactive memory systems for the team members, identifying who knows what and who has which skills.",1523422319886300.pdf
"This exercise also begins to develop the team’s cognition, the organized understanding of collective knowledge among team members (Mohammed & Dumville, 2001).",1523422319886300.pdf
"The second section requires group members to identify what the team’s task goals 
and process goals are.",1523422319886300.pdf
"During this stage, if this was being used for a multidisciplinary research effort, it would be recommended to include a row on problem identification.",1523422319886300.pdf
Identifying the problem is a critical step prior to assigning tasks and process goals.,1523422319886300.pdf
This step initiates the communication and coordination steps of teamwork by requiring each team member to identify and agree on the listed goals.,1523422319886300.pdf
The following section of the form identifies who will do what along with who is appointed as the team leader.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Not all teams operate with a team leader, some utilize shared leadership models or incorporate a blend of coaching and leadership.",1523422319886300.pdf
Either is fine; it is more a matter of what works best for the team.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Also, this section identifies who is to complete what assignment or task.",1523422319886300.pdf
Next in the form is a section on the team’s rules of conduct.,1523422319886300.pdf
"The team decides on 
how they wish to conduct business.",1523422319886300.pdf
The section on evaluation includes a debriefing session after a milestone or after a set of subtasks have been completed.,1523422319886300.pdf
This debrief-ing is part of a continuous learning cycle; team members identify what worked and,1523422319886300.pdf
"80 Advances in Developing Human Resources 22(1)
Figure 2.",1523422319886300.pdf
Team agreement contract.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Turner and Baker 81
what did not work as well as planned, then discuss options to make the teamwork 
processes work better during the next cycle.",1523422319886300.pdf
The last section involves each team mem-ber agreeing to the information on the form and willing to adopt the changes recom-mended by the team for the next cycle.,1523422319886300.pdf
"This process of having the team agree to the team’s goals, coordination, communi-
cation, and leadership begins the process of managing the emerging states of team-work.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Scholar-practitioners can utilize this form when working in team settings with their customer, whereas scholars can easily modify this form for use in any type of cross-disciplinary research activity.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Furthermore, this form has been used successfully in a number of team tasks in the classroom, which can benefit both scholars and stu-dents.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Utilization of this form addresses each of the critical techniques of strengthen-ing teamwork to (Bennett & Gadlin, 2012)
••Foster an environment that is collegial and nonthreatening.",1523422319886300.pdf
••Openly recognize strengths of all members of the team and discuss how these different strengths contribute to advancing the project.,1523422319886300.pdf
••Take a few minutes at regularly scheduled group meetings to do a check-in.,1523422319886300.pdf
Ask how everyone is doing.,1523422319886300.pdf
••Encourage open and honest discussion by establishing trust.,1523422319886300.pdf
••Jointly develop a process for bringing issues and disagreements forward for early resolution.,1523422319886300.pdf
"••Assure that when decisions are being made, which require everyone’s input, that each person has an opportunity and understands the process for providing comment.",1523422319886300.pdf
"••Schedule periodic assessments and feedback, including opportunities for col-laborators to discuss what is going well, what is not, and what needs to be improved.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Implications for HRD Practitioners
Practitioners will need to be even more aware of how to gain credit when contributing to a collaborative research project, how to gain funding for collaborative research projects.",1523422319886300.pdf
"In addition, scholar-practitioners will also need to know how to show impact from their collaborative efforts to better advance one’s self for promotion and tenure.",1523422319886300.pdf
These items are discussed in the following sections.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Author’s Contribution
Additional questions have been raised as to how to account for each author’s contribu-tion to a multiauthor research paper.",1523422319886300.pdf
"This collaborative contribution record aids in displaying an individual author’s impact to their field, typically by citation counts, but it also contributes to the author’s evaluation for promotion and tenure.",1523422319886300.pdf
Contribution should be decided upon the following criteria set by the Committee on Publication Ethics (COPE):,1523422319886300.pdf
"82 Advances in Developing Human Resources 22(1)
1.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Substantial contributions to conception and design, or acquisition of data, or 
analysis and interpretation of data;
2.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Drafting the article or revising it critically for important intellectual content; and
3.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Final approval of the version to be published (Albert & Wager, 2003).",1523422319886300.pdf
Authorship contribution should be based on each author meeting all three conditions throughout the research and writing processes.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Discussions relating to the order of authorship should begin during the start of any research project rather than later as well as publication and conference intentions of the final output (Albert & Wager, 2003).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Contribution can be evaluated in two general methods: the full counting approach 
and the fractional counting approach (Rahman et al., 2017).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Full counting provides credit to each author for an article’s citation, whereas fractional counting partitions the citation into a part per each author such that each author would receive one (cita-tion) divided by the number of authors (n ; 1/n).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Different variations of this fractional 
approach can be found in the literature (see Rahman et al., 2017).",1523422319886300.pdf
"The point remains, however, that attribution for an author’s contribution in multiauthored papers is cur -
rently being considered within academia.",1523422319886300.pdf
"These discussions have the potential of negatively impacting one’s academic career if, for example, one’s contribution was unfairly measured using a fractional measure that assigned the researcher little to no credit for participation in the multiauthored contribution.",1523422319886300.pdf
"This could deeply impact one’s chances of being promoted to a tenured faculty position, further highlighting the need for scholars and students (emerging scholars) to be able to counter such practices.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Funding
Other problems that accompany this trend of cross-disciplinary research is that national and international funding agencies are beginning to require that research be conducted by cross-disciplinary teams, typically of the variety of multidisciplinary or transdisci-plinary research teams due to the complexity involved in today’s environment and problems (Zucker, 2012).",1523422319886300.pdf
Funding agencies have been encouraged to support cross-disciplinary efforts.,1523422319886300.pdf
One example of this is in the Global Research Council’s (GRC) report on interdisci-plinarity.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Regarding recommendations to funding agencies, the GRC provided the following:
••Our research and much of the literature suggest that top-down thematic funding programs are one of the most common approaches adopted by funders to encourage interdisciplinarity.",1523422319886300.pdf
••There is also a consensus that researcher-led “bottom-up” approaches are required and funding agencies should support such approaches despite the potential risks associated with the most innovative ideas.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Turner and Baker 83
••At the same time, interdisciplinary research should be viewed as a means to an 
end and not an end in itself.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Several funding agencies emphasized that practices and policies toward interdisciplinarity should be driven by the required out-comes and scientific demand (Gleed & Marchant, 2016).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Promotion and Tenure Practices
Typically, academic institutions’ promotion and tenure policies still favor individual research (Rylance, 2015).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Also, current bibliometrics favor individual efforts as opposed to providing collaborative measures.",1523422319886300.pdf
"This results, in many cases for early career aca-demics, in advisement against cross-collaborative research in favor of concentrating one’s time and effort on research that is individual, unidisciplinary, or both (Rylance, 2015).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Future changes in promotion and tenure practices will need to be considered, especially with current and future changes to the requirements from grant-funding insti-tutions.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Scholars and scholar-practitioners will be better served to collaborate, joining academia with practice, to gain future funding for research.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Receipt of such funding could potentially be the catalyst to change the requirements for promotion and tenure, at least at one’s current institution.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Evaluation Techniques
There are various evaluation measures for collaboration and transdisciplinary research projects.",1523422319886300.pdf
"One such tool is the research orientation scale provided by the National Cancer Institute (NCI; Fload Expert, 2010).",1523422319886300.pdf
This tool is available free and is included as part of the Team Science Toolkit sponsored by NCI (https://www.teamsciencetool-kit.cancer.gov/Public/Home.aspx).,1523422319886300.pdf
Another evaluation tool is the transdisciplinary ori-entation scale provided by Mirsa et al.,1523422319886300.pdf
(2015).,1523422319886300.pdf
"The transdisciplinary orientation scale provides “a reliable and preliminarily validated tool to measure scientists’ and schol-ars’ personal disposition toward transdisciplinary research” (Mirsa et al., 2015, p. 6).",1523422319886300.pdf
"These evaluation tools could be tested and validated for collaborative research 
within the HRD community.",1523422319886300.pdf
Future research could entail utilizing either of these eval-uation tools to identify the level of collaboration among collectives along with extend-ing HRD’s knowledge base by introducing new evaluation tools that could be used by scholars and scholar-practitioners within the field of HRD.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Conclusion
Research is a collaborative process.",1523422319886300.pdf
"Advances in science rely partially on social inter -
action among other scientists (Katz & Martin, 1997).",1523422319886300.pdf
"These interactions have, in some cases, formed into larger, organized, collaborative networks such as the Academy of Human Resource Development (AHRD) and the SciTS.",1523422319886300.pdf
Funding agencies have also begun to require applicants to show collaborative efforts when documenting research compared with single-discipline research.,1523422319886300.pdf
Part of this drive for more cross-disciplinary research is because “it has a key role to play in addressing the grand challenges that,1523422319886300.pdf
"84 Advances in Developing Human Resources 22(1)
society faces” (Gleed & Marchant, 2016, p. 5).",1523422319886300.pdf
"Multiauthorship research is more com-
mon in many disciplines and has been shown to already be acceptable in HRD.",1523422319886300.pdf
"This shift toward collaborative research identifies with the theme of this special 
issue in that it identifies the shifting roles that scholars and scholar-practitioners will face shortly regarding cross-disciplinary research.",1523422319886300.pdf
The potential changes in policies required from the new demands of cross-disciplinary research to gain funding will indeed impact the future of current and emerging scholars.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Managing and adjusting the collaborative processes, current practices, and policies 
will take time.",1523422319886300.pdf
These items are critical and must be realized for scholars and scholar-practitioners to advance into the future of collaborative research.,1523422319886300.pdf
"Achieving emer -
gence, through collaborative research practices, is essential for those who practice HRD as it is a multidisciplinary field of study.",1523422319886300.pdf
"This emergence addresses the theme of this special issue, Changing of the Guard.",1523422319886300.pdf
Scholars and scholar-practitioners need to be responsive and adaptable to this transformation.,1523422319886300.pdf
They must be capable of participat-ing in managing and evaluating new collaborative efforts.,1523422319886300.pdf
"These efforts will benefit HRD scholars and scholar-practitioners and could begin a new field of study within HRD, TSci, and Cross-Disciplinary Research.",1523422319886300.pdf
