NeuroView",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
of associated platform papers.,1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Our cur-
rent 10-year plan calls for continual thrice
yearly releases of data.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"We also share
white papers describing in minute detailour operating procedures and methods
and many of our tools, such as transgenic
animals and viruses (e.g., Madisen et al.,
2010 ).",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Indeed, The Jackson Laboratory
has shipped more than 20,000 of our
transgenic mice to customers worldwide.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Whydo we pursue such an ‘‘information-
wants-to-be-free’’ policy?",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"The simplest
answer is that this is the vision of Paul
Allen.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"His intent is that Institute resourcesshould accelerate neuroscience discov-
ery.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"He also believes that the Institute
should act as an example of what everylaboratory should be doing.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"For millennials, communicating via texts
and images is part of their social onlineexperience growing up.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Thus, it comesnatural to young scientists to freely and
openly share data, computer code, and
manuscripts.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Indeed, open science hasbeen advocated for and practiced by a
small number of neuroscientists for more
than a decade (e.g., Van Horn and Gazza-
niga, 2013; Glasser et al., 2016 ).",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Regret-
tably, however, the vast majority of data
and metadata in the neurosciences con-tinues to remain inaccessible.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"It is urgent that the ﬁeld as a whole
move toward an open science policy, as
it will alleviate some of the root causesof the replication crisis so pervasive in
biomedical research.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"A recent review on
this topic ( Button et al., 2013 ) opens with
an eye-catching, ‘‘It has been claimed
and demonstrated that many (and
possibly most) of the conclusions drawnfrom biomedical research are probably
false.’’ Estimates for the fraction of false
ﬁndings range from a simple majority to
80% and higher ( Open Science Collabo-
ration, 2015 ).",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Given that replication is
one of the key steps in the scientiﬁc pro-
cess, its systematic failure for so manypublished ﬁndings constitute a strikingdeparture from good scientiﬁc practice
that could come back to haunt the ﬁeld.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
This cannot be eluded by blithely ignoringit as most scientists are wont to do.,1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"There are two broad categories of
causes for the replication crisis.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"First, even simple organisms have
vastly more degrees of freedom than the
natural, non-evolved systems physiciststypically deal with, such as elementary
particles, gravity waves, or exo-planets.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Thus, while a Higgs Boson has the samesignature no matter where on Earth it isdetected, a C57BL/6J mouse in Seattle
will not be the same as a laboratory
mouse in Boston ( Crabbe et al., 1999 ).",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"What is true for standard breeds of mice
kept under controlled conditions is vastly
more so for ‘‘neuro-typical’’ volunteersor patients.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Mitigating this problem will
not be easy but must include enforcing,
to the maximal extent possible, standard-ization of model systems, procedures,tools, and instruments, as well as meticu-
lously publicizing all logistical and meth-
odological details.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Unbiased surveyseliminate some sources of these statisti-
cal infelicities and have found widespread
adoptions in some ﬁelds.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"For example,within astronomy, generations of Sloan
Digital Sky surveys have resulted in more
than 5,000 refereed publications and 200million SQL queries to the relevant data-
base and revolutionized the ﬁeld in the
process ( Burns et al., 2014 ).",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"A second set of causes relate to lack of
statistical ‘‘hygiene,’’ including low statis-
tical power, incorrect noise models, pub-
lication bias (or ‘‘the ﬁle drawer problem’’),hypothesizing after the results are known(HARKing), and p-hacking.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"These phe-
nomena have been much commented
upon ( Ioannidis 2005; Button et al.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
2013 ).,1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"The latest scandal follows the re-analysis
of resting-state fMRI data from the public
database Functional Connectomes Proj-
ect(Eklund et al., 2016 ), which revealed
that widely used analysis software pack-
ages yield false-positive rates of up to70%.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"This may affect more than 3,000
published fMRI studies, funded at great
expense by the public purse.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"There is no question that making all
data and metadata, together with all
computational and statistical procedures
of every publication freely and publicly
available would address some of these
shortcomings (see Box 1 ).",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Such a policy
allows researchers to easily test whetherthe published conclusions are valid,
particularly when they conﬂict with other
studies.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Given the potential threat to thereputation of the authors, Open Scienceis likely to lead to statistically more valid
results than otherwise.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Open access
also allows for analysis of published datausing different algorithms and assump-
tions to gain additional or alternative in-
sights, or to ask questions that were notconceived by the original authors.",1-s2.0-S0896627316307206-main.pdf
"Finally,
open data sharing enables the aggrega-
