I.,20023981.pdf
"The Origins of Big Team Science 
 The emergence of the large interdisciplinary scientific team as the 
 landmark of science can be traced to at least three separate develop 
 ments.",20023981.pdf
"First is the extraordinary growth of science and the resulting in 
 crease in the amount of scientific information produced; second is the 
 emergence and institutionalization of applied science; third, and pos 
 sibly most important, is the increasing complexity of scientific machinery.",20023981.pdf
A.,20023981.pdf
"The Information Crisis and the Rise of Team Science 
 The scientific information explosion has caused scientists to become 
 more specialized.",20023981.pdf
"Some scientists respond to the information crisis by 
 confining their range of scientific undertakings to those over which they  can still retain command of the relevant information sources.",20023981.pdf
"Others 
 form interdisciplinary teams in which are represented different though 
 overlapping ranges of expertise or technique.",20023981.pdf
"In principle, the problems 
 that can be tackled successfully by such teams ought to be more com 
 plex than those tackled by individuals.",20023981.pdf
"This trend in the sociology of science was foreshadowed in an essay, 
 ""The Limits of Science,"" by Eugene Wigner in 1950.5 Wigner argued 
 that, for the reason I have mentioned, team research in which individual 
 scientists are orchestrated into a productive whole by a scientific leader  would become more common.",20023981.pdf
"He then asked how this new social struc 
 ture would change the course of science.",20023981.pdf
"Could the theory of relativity 
 or the Schrodinger equation have been discovered by an interdisciplinary 
 team?",20023981.pdf
"Or, for that matter, could the mysteries of the ""omega-minus"" 
 particle and violation of charge-parity invariance (both discoveries of 
 teams of high-energy physicists ) have been unearthed by the typical in 
 dividual scientist of the nineteenth century?",20023981.pdf
"I shall return to these ques 
 tions later.",20023981.pdf
"The information explosion has been the subject of many essays and 
 studies.",20023981.pdf
"Here I will mention only how the spawning of the scientific in 
 formation specialist has affected the organization of scientific research.",20023981.pdf
"In previous generations the scientist gathered his information more or 
 less on his own and rather haphazardly.",20023981.pdf
"Today scientists of course con 
 tinue to browse in this manner, but they are now backed by a host of 
 information services, ranging from libraries to abstract services and 
 specialized information centers.",20023981.pdf
"Already one can see the considerable influence of the information 
