 over which he can comfortably retain command.",20023981.pdf
"Thus basic science ( at 
 least before the advent of the big machine) with its internally generated 
 problems, can be pursued adequately within a narrow discipline.",20023981.pdf
"If the 
 problem takes the researcher out of his specialty, he is still observing the 
 canons of pure science if he turns to a different problem that is more 
 easily accommodated by his interest and competence.",20023981.pdf
"It is for this rea 
 son that much of basic science can remain disciplinary and little: the 
 interdisciplinary team is not its social characteristic.",20023981.pdf
"Of course, even as a description of basic little science this is over 
 simplified; to characterize science as the art of the soluble tells only part 
 of the story.",20023981.pdf
"Basic science, at its best, is the art of the soluble and the 
 important (as Medawar himself recognizes).",20023981.pdf
"Researchers, even poor 
 ones, usually have more ideas than they have resources with which to 
 pursue them; their research strategy always amounts to choosing, from 
 among a variety of soluble problems, the ones they regard as important.",20023981.pdf
What constitutes importance in science?,20023981.pdf
"One, though certainly not the 
 only, criterion is the degree to which a given piece of science relates to 
 neighboring sciences.",20023981.pdf
"Indeed, the motivation for much basic scientific 
 activity originates outside that activity.",20023981.pdf
"Sometimes the motivation lies 
 in a neighboring basic science.",20023981.pdf
"For instance, a nuclear physicist may 
 study light-element reactions because these are needed by an astro 
 physicist who wants to understand the mechanism of stellar evolution.",20023981.pdf
"Sometimes the motivation lies in technology: a physicist may investigate 
 the basic properties of plasmas because of their relevance to the con 
 trolled release of thermonuclear energy.",20023981.pdf
"But the main point is that as 
 soon as a scientist ventures to deal with a question arising in a field 
 outside his discipline he has less control over where to look for a solu 
 tion.",20023981.pdf
"He no longer has the luxury of narrowing the problem to what is 
 soluble with his own expertise.",20023981.pdf
